data.title: United Parks & Resorts Inc. reported Q4 2025: 4.8M guests, $373.5M revenue, $15.1M net income, Adjusted EBITDA $115.2M. Fiscal 2025: 21.2M guests, $1.7B revenue, $168.4M net income, Adjusted EBITDA $605.1M. Share repurchases and animal rescue efforts highlighted. Investment in new rides and attractions expected to boost attendance and revenue in 2026. Declines in attendance and revenue per capita reported. CEO optimistic for financial performance in 2026. Conference call held to discuss results. Non-GAAP financial measures used in reporting. Numerous accolades received in 2025. Future uncertainties highlighted in forward-looking statements. Contact info provided. [Char. count: 392]
data.description: United Parks & Resorts Inc. reported its financial results for Q4 2025 and fiscal year 2025. In Q4 2025, attendance was 4.8 million guests, revenue was $373.5 million, net income was $15.1 million, and adjusted EBITDA was $115.2 million. For fiscal year 2025, attendance was 21.2 million guests, revenue was $1.7 billion, net income was $168.4 million, and adjusted EBITDA was $605.1 million. This marks a decrease in revenue and attendance from the previous year. The company also engaged in share repurchases and animal rescue efforts during the period. Key performance metrics saw a decrease in revenue per capita and admission per capita, with an increase in in-park per capita spending. The company outlined plans for 2026, focusing on new attractions and cost management to enhance financial performance. The company's CEO expressed confidence in the initiatives. The company also received accolades in 2025, and highlighted new rides and attractions planned for 2026. Additional information, including non-GAAP financial measures, statements regarding forward-looking information, and contact information, was provided in the news article.

data.title: Weber is recalling more than 3.2 million metal wire bristle grill brushes due to an ingestion hazard.
data.description: Product Name: Metal Wire Bristle Grill Brushes are being recalled due to a hazard where small metal wire bristles can come loose from the brushes and adhere to the grill or food. This poses a risk of ingestion and serious internal injuries, potentially leading to the need for surgery. Consumers are advised to discontinue use of these brushes and should opt for a replacement immediately to ensure safety.
